Application Description
Application Support
AmTherapy application is an Android application designed primarily for pediatricians, pediatric students of medical schools.

1.1 This Application is not an advertising resource and is intended for calculating the dosages of the most common forms of drug release, calculating the energy requirements of children with PEM, and assessing the physical development of the child. All calculations are made in accordance with the current drug instructions (minimum and maximum single dosages, maximum daily dosage), as well as WHO recommendations for assessing the physical development of the child and feeding rules. The calculation of the basal metabolic rate for children is also based on the WHO recommendations (values of conversion factors for calculating energy requirements).
1.2 AmTherapy is a free resource that aims to simplify calculations of a pediatric healthcare professional.
1.3 Application User (hereinafter the User) - an individual who has installed this application on a mobile device, as well as being its user.
1.4 Application Developer (hereinafter referred to as the Developer) - the person who manages the Application and other actions related to its use.

Basic metabolic rate calculation (children under one year old)
Calculation of basal metabolic rate for children under one year old (kcal / day): \n boys: (60.9 x weight in kg) –54 \n girls: (61 x weight in kg) –51
Formula for calculating the patient\'s actual energy requirement (actual energy expenditure): \n DRE = OO x FA x FZ x FR x FP x TF x DMT
Be careful! Different countries use different correction factors. \n Indicate only those that you see fit. Odds not listed are 1.0

Appropriate body weight / feed volume

Continued monthly body weight is calculated based on the baby's birth weight, based on the newborn baby's lightweight (if any). 
 Boundaries of changes in the calculation of the newborn's body weight: 2500g, 2000g, 1500g, 1000g 
 The daily feeding volume is calculated according to the required body weight (MT): 
 0-2 months = 1/5 MT 
 3-4 months = 1/6 MT 
 5-6 months = 1/7 MT 
 7-8 months = 1/8 MT 
 9-12 months = 1/9 MT

• The method of administration and dosage of a particular drug depends on its form of release and other factors. It is necessary to strictly observe compliance with the used dosage form of a specific drug, indications for use and dosage regimen. 
 • Store all drugs in a dark place out of the reach of children. 
 • To prepare a suspension, it is recommended to dilute the powder with boiled water at room temperature to the mark on the jar of the drug. 
 • The prepared suspension should be stored in the refrigerator. 
 • Before giving the suspension to the child, be sure to shake the contents of the jar. 
 • The course of taking antibacterial drugs starts when they are prescribed by a doctor. 
 • Follow the prescribed regimen of antibacterial medication completely, even if you feel better. 
 • Suppositories are stored in packaging, protected from light, at temperatures from +8 to +15 ° C, unless otherwise indicated in the regulatory documentation. 
 • Before sticking a suppository to a child, it is necessary to squeeze the candle in your hand for a short time, so it will become softer and certainly does not injure the mucous membrane. 
 • When a child has an acute respiratory infection, try to maintain an abundant drinking regime. 
 • Be sure to check the expiration date of the medicinal product. 
 
 Cheers!

Always keep in mind the problem of antibiotic resistance. 
 Key WHO recommendations for healthcare professionals to prevent resistance. 
 • If you think the patient may need antibiotics, if possible, do a confirmatory test to find out which antibiotic is needed. 
 • Only prescribe and dispense antibiotics when they are really needed, according to current guidelines. 
 • Prescribe and dispense appropriate antibiotics at the required dosage and course of administration. 
 • Prevent infections - keep your hands, tools and environment clean. 
 • Make sure your patients get vaccinated on time. 
 
 Good luck in your hard work!

Standard dosages of antibacterial drugs are based on guidelines and clinical protocols! 
 The standard dosage can be changed ONLY by the doctor at his own discretion. 
 Unconsciously changing the dosage can harm the health of the child and even lead to death!

In this window you can change the standard dosage of drugs. 
 In order to change the dosage, select the drug you are interested in, delete the current value and enter your own. 
 Do NOT leave the fields blank, otherwise you will not be able to save the changes! 
 In order to save the values you have changed, click the "Change Dosages" button. 
 If you leave this window by changing the values, but without clicking on "Change Dosages", your changes will NOT be saved. Carefully follow the dosage of which drug / drugs you are changing. If you enter to return the standard values, click "Return Standard Values".

 E43: Severe protein-energy malnutrition, unspecified 
 Severe weight loss in children or adults, or no weight gain in a child that results in the measured weight being at least 3 standard deviations below the reference group mean (or a similar weight loss reflected by others statistical methods). If only one measurement of body weight is available, then severe wasting is more likely to be said when the body weight detected is 3 or more standard deviations below the average for the reference population. 
 Included: hungry edema. 
 
 E44: Moderate to mild protein-energy malnutrition 
 (E44.0) Moderate protein-energy malnutrition: 
 Loss of body weight in children or adults, or no weight gain in a child, which causes the detected body weight to be 2 standard deviations or more below the average for the reference population, but less than 3 standard deviations ( or a similar decrease in body weight reflected by other statistical methods). If only a single measurement of body weight is available, then moderate protein-energy malnutrition with a high degree of probability can be talked about when the detected body weight is 2 or more standard deviations below the average for the reference population. 
 (E44.1) Mild protein-energy malnutrition: 
 Loss of body weight in children or adults, or no weight gain in a child, which causes the detected body weight to be below the average for the reference population by 1 or more but less than 2 standard deviations (or similar weight loss reflected by other statistical methods). If data from only a single measurement of body weight are available, then mild protein-energy malnutrition is most likely to be talked about when the detected body weight is 1 or more, but less than 2 standard deviations below the average for the reference population.

F00 *: Dementia in Alzheimer's disease (G30.-) 
 (F00.0 *) Dementia in early-onset Alzheimer's disease (G30.0): 
 Dementia in Alzheimer's disease, which began before the age of 65, is relatively rapidly progressive and is characterized by pronounced various disorders of the higher cortical functions. 
 • Alzheimer's disease type 2 
 • Presenile dementia, Alzheimer's type 
 • Primary degenerative dementia, Alzheimer's type, presenile onset 
 (F00.1 *) Dementia in late-onset Alzheimer's disease (G30.1): 
 Dementia in Alzheimer's disease, onset after age 65 (usually at age 70 and later), is slowly progressive and is characterized by severe memory impairment as the main symptom. 
 • Alzheimer's disease type 1 
 • Primary degenerative dementia, Alzheimer's type, senile onset 
 • Senile dementia, Alzheimer's type 
 (F00.2 *) Dementia in Alzheimer's disease, atypical or mixed (G30.8): 
 • Atypical dementia, Alzheimer's type 
 (F00.9 *) Unspecified dementia in Alzheimer's disease (G30.9) 
 
 F01: Vascular Dementia 
 Included: atherosclerotic dementia 
 (F01.0) Acute onset vascular dementia 
 Usually develops rapidly after a series of strokes due to cerebrovascular thrombosis, embolism or hemorrhage. Less commonly, one major cerebral infarction may be the cause. 
 (F01.1) Multi-infarction dementia: 
 Gradual onset associated with repeated transient ischemic conditions that lead to the accumulation of infarction foci in the brain parenchyma. 
 • Predominantly cortical dementia 
 (F01.2) Subcortical vascular dementia 
 Includes cases characterized by a history of hypertension and ischemic destructive foci in the deep layers of the white matter of the cerebral hemispheres. The cerebral cortex is usually preserved, and this contrasts with the clinical picture of dementia in Alzheimer's disease. 
 (F01.3) Mixed cortical and subcortical vascular dementia 
 (F01.8) Other vascular dementia 
 (F01.9) Vascular dementia, unspecified 
 
 F02 *: Dementia in other diseases classified elsewhere 
 Cases of dementia associated with (or suspected to be associated with) causes other than Alzheimer's disease or cerebrovascular disease. The disease can begin at any age, but less often in old age. 
 (F02.0 *) Dementia in Pick's disease (G31.0) 
 Progressive dementia that begins in middle age, characterized by early, slowly progressive changes in character and social degradation, decreased intelligence, memory and speech function, combined with indifference, euphoria and sometimes extrapyramidal phenomena. 
 (F02.1 *) Dementia in Creutzfeldt-Jakob disease (A81.0) 
 Progressive dementia with extensive neurologic symptoms due to specific alterations in the nervous system suspected to be caused by a transmissible agent. Usually begins in middle or old age, although it can develop at any other adulthood. The course is subacute, death occurs in 1-2 years. 
 (F02.2 *) Dementia in Huntington's disease (G10): 
 Dementia, which develops as one of the manifestations of extensive brain degeneration. This disorder is inherited in an autosomal dominant manner. Symptoms usually appear in the third or fourth decade of life. Slowly progressive disease leads to death usually in 10-15 years. 
 • Dementia with Huntington's chorea 
 (F02.3 *) Dementia in Parkinson's disease (G20): 
 Dementia that develops in the course of Parkinson's disease. Does not have any special characteristic clinical signs. 
 • Dementia with: 
 - trembling paralysis 
 -parkinsonism 
 (F02.4 *) Dementia in human immunodeficiency virus disease [HIV] (B22.0) 
 Dementia that develops during the course of an illness caused by HIV, in the absence of other comorbidities or conditions besides HIV infection, which could explain the clinical picture.

 F06: Other mental disorders due to brain damage and dysfunction or medical illness 
 This heading includes mixed conditions causally associated with cerebral disorders due to primary brain disease, systemic disease secondary to brain damage, exposure to exogenous toxic substances or hormones, endocrine disorders or other somatic diseases. 
 (F06.0) Organic hallucinosis: 
 A disorder with persistent or recurrent hallucinations, usually visual or auditory, that occur with clear consciousness and may (not always) be perceived as such by the patient. There may be a delusional interpretation of hallucinations, but delusion does not dominate the clinical picture; understanding of the environment can be preserved. 
 • Organic hallucinatory state (non-alcoholic) 
 (F06.1) Organic catatonic state 
 (F06.2) Organic delusional [schizophrenic] disorder: 
 A disorder in which the clinical picture is dominated by persistent or recurrent delusions. Delusions may be accompanied by hallucinations. There may be some symptoms that make you think of schizophrenia, such as bizarre hallucinations or thought disorder. 
 • Paranoid and paranoid-hallucinatory organic states 
 • Schizophrenia-like psychosis in epilepsy 
 (F06.3) Organic mood disorders [affective] 
 Disorders characterized by changes in mood or affect, usually accompanied by changes in general level of activity, depression, hypomania, mania, or bipolar states (see F30-F38), but arising as a consequence of organic disease. 
 (F06.4) Organic Anxiety Disorder 
 A disorder characterized by the main features of generalized anxiety disorder (F41.1) or panic disorder (F41.0), or a combination of both, but arising as a consequence of an organic disorder. 
 (F06.5) Organic Dissociative Disorder 
 A disorder characterized by partial or complete loss of normal integration between memory of the past, awareness of oneself as a person, direct sensation and control of body movement (F44.-), but arising as a consequence of an organic disorder. 
 (F06.6) Organic emotionally labile [asthenic] disorder 
 A disorder characterized by emotional incontinence or lability, fatigue, many unpleasant physical sensations (such as dizziness) and pain, but arising from an organic disorder. 
 (F06.7) Mild cognitive impairment

The following fourth characters are used in headings F10-F19: 
 .0 Acute intoxication 
 .1 Harmful use 
 The use of a psychotropic substance that is detrimental to health. The damage can be physical (as in cases of hepatitis from self-prescription of injected psychotropic substances) or mental (for example, episodes of depressive disorder with prolonged alcohol use). 
 • Psychotropic substance abuse 
 .2 Addiction Syndrome 
 A group of behavioral, mnestic and physiological phenomena that develop with repeated use of a substance, which include a strong desire to take a drug, lack of self-control, use despite harmful consequences, a higher priority of drug use over other actions and obligations, increased tolerance to substances. 
 • Addiction syndrome can refer to a specific psychotropic substance (such as tobacco, alcohol or diazepam), a class of substances (such as opioid drugs), or a wider range of different psychotropic substances. 
 • Chronic chronic alcoholism 
 • Dipsomania 
 • Addiction 
 .3 Withdrawal Syndrome 
 A group of symptoms of various combinations and severity levels arising from absolute or relative withdrawal from the use of a psychoactive substance after constant use of this substance. The onset and course of the withdrawal state are time-limited and are related to the type of psychoactive substance and the dose taken immediately before the cessation of use or dose reduction. Withdrawal states can be complicated by seizures. 
 .4 Withdrawal syndrome with delirium 
 A condition in which the abstinence described above (common fourth sign .3) is complicated by delirium described in F05.-. This condition can also be accompanied by seizures. If an organic factor plays a role in the etiology of the disorder, the condition should be classified under F05.8. 
 • Delirium tremens (alcoholic) 
 .5 Psychotic disorder 
 A complex of psychotic symptoms that occur during or after the use of a psychoactive substance, which, however, cannot be explained only by acute intoxication and which are not part of the withdrawal state. The disorder is characterized by hallucinations (usually auditory, but often of several types), perception disorders, delusions (often paranoid or persecutory), psychomotor disorders (agitation or stupor), abnormal affectation, ranging from intense fear to ecstasy. Consciousness is usually clear, but there may be some degree of clouding, but without severe confusion. 
 • Alcoholic (th): 
 -hallucinosis 
 - delirium of jealousy 
 -paranoia 
 -psychosis NOS 
 .6 Amnestic Syndrome 
 A syndrome characterized by a pronounced chronic decrease in memory for recent and distant events. Direct recall of events is usually not disturbed. Memory for recent events is usually more impaired than for distant ones. Usually, there is a clear violation of the sense of time and sequence of events and there are difficulties in mastering new material. Confabulation is possible, but not required. Other cognitive functions are usually relatively well preserved, and amnestic disorders are disproportionate to the severity of other disorders. 
 • Amnestic disorder associated with the use of alcohol or other psychoactive substances. 
 • Korsakov's psychosis or syndrome associated with the use of alcohol or other psychoactive substances, or without specification. 
 • With complementary code, (E51.2, G32.8 *), if necessary when the disorder is associated with Wernicke's disease or syndrome. 
 .7 Residual state and psychotic disorder with delayed onset 
 A disorder in which cognitive, emotional, personality, or behavioral impairment caused by alcohol or substance use may persist beyond a period during which the substance is directly exposed. The onset of the disorder must be directly attributable to substance use. Cases in which the onset of the onset of the disorder occurs later than the episode (s) of substance use may be coded with the above fourth character only if it is clearly proven that the disorder belongs to the residual effects of the psychoactive substance. 
 • Residual phenomena can be distinguished from a psychotic state in part by their episodicity, mainly of short duration, by their duplication of previous alcohol or drug manifestations. 
 • Alcoholic dementia NOS 
 • Chronic alcoholic cerebral syndrome 
 • Dementia and other mild forms of persistent cognitive impairment 
 • "Flashbacks" 
 • Delayed substance use disorder 
 • Perceptual impairment after using a hallucinogen 
 • Residual: 
 -emotional [affective] disorder 
 -personality and behavior disorder 
 .8 Other mental and behavioral disorders due to substance use 
 .9 Substance use mental and behavioral disorder, unspecified

To identify the degree of mental disability, headings F70-F79 are used with the following fourth character:

 F70: Mild mental retardation 
 Estimated IQ is 50-69 (in adulthood, mental development corresponds to that of 9-12 years old). Some learning difficulties in school are likely. Many adults will be able to work, maintain normal social relationships and contribute to society. 
 Included: 
 -dementia 
 - moderate subnormality and 
 
 F71: Moderate mental retardation 
 Estimated IQ ranges from 35 to 49 (in adulthood, mental development corresponds to development at the age of 6-9 years). Probably a noticeable developmental delay from childhood, but the majority can learn and achieve a certain degree of independence in self-service, acquire adequate communication and study skills. Adults will need different types of support at home and at work. 
 Included: moderate mental subnormality 
 
 F72: Severe mental retardation 
 Estimated IQ ranges from 20 to 34 (in adulthood, mental development corresponds to development at the age of 3-6 years). May require ongoing support. 
 Included: pronounced mental subnormality 
 
 F73: Deep mental retardation 
 Indicative IQ below 20 (in adulthood, mental development is below development at the age of three). The result is severe limitation of self-care, communication and mobility, as well as increased sexuality. 
 Included: deep mental subnormality

 Z62: Other parenting issues 
 (Z62.0) Inadequate parental care and supervision: 
 • Parents lack of awareness of what the child is doing and where he is, poor control over him, lack of constant care for him and attempts to prevent risky situations in which he may find himself. 
 (Z62.1) Excessive parental guardianship: 
 • The upbringing system, the result of which is infantilism and the child's lack of independence and independence. 
 (Z62.2) Education in a closed institution: 
 • Group parenting, in which the responsibility of the parents is largely shifted to the staff of various forms of institutions (such as children's homes, orphanages, boarding schools) or long-term therapeutic care in a hospital, convalescent institution or sanatorium when the child is without at least one parent. 
 (Z62.3) Child hostility and unfair claims: 
 • Negative attitude of parents towards the child as a person, harshness and constant irritability in relation to certain moments in the child's behavior (for example, constant insults for any actions in the house or vain accusations of the child). 
 (Z62.4) Emotional abandonment of children: 
 • The tone of the conversation between parent and child is dismissive or indifferent. Lack of interest in the child, a sensitive attitude to his difficulties, praise and support, an irritable reaction to a violation in the child's behavior and the lack of an affectionate and warm attitude towards the child. 
 (Z62.5) Other parenting deficiencies: 
 • Lack of learning and play experience for the child 
 (Z62.6) Unacceptable parental pressure and other negative parenting factors: 
 • Parents force the child to do something that goes beyond the accepted norms, does not correspond to gender (for example, dressing a boy in a girl's dress), age (for example, requiring the child to be responsible for his actions), his wishes or capabilities. 
 (Z62.8) Other clarified parenting issues 
 (Z62.9) Child-rearing problem, unspecified

 U07: Emergency Use 
 Codes U00-U49 should be used to temporarily assign new diseases of unknown etiology. In emergencies, codes are not always available on electronic systems. The U07 category specifications allow them to be used in every electronic system at any time on behalf of WHO immediately. 
 (U07.1) COVID-19, virus identified 
 Use this code when COVID-19 has been confirmed by laboratory tests, regardless of the severity of the clinical signs or symptoms. If necessary, indicate pneumonia or other manifestations of infection, use an additional code. 
 (U07.2) COVID-19, no virus identified: 
 • COVID-19 NOS 
 Use this code if COVID-19 is diagnosed clinically or epidemiologically but laboratory tests are inconclusive or not available. If necessary, indicate pneumonia or other manifestations of infection, use an additional code.

 U08: Personal history of COVID-19 
 (U08.9) Personal history of COVID-19, unspecified 
 This additional code is used to record an earlier confirmed or probable episode of COVID-19 that affects a person's health condition and the person no longer has COVID-19. This code should not be used to compile primary life tables. 
 
 U09: Status after COVID-19 
 (U09.9) Post-COVID-19 status, unspecified: 
 This optional code allows you to communicate with COVID-19. It should not be used in cases where the COVID-19 pathogen is still present in the body. 
 • Postmoid state 
 • Postcoid syndrome 
 
 U10: Multisystem Inflammatory Syndrome Associated with COVID-19 
 (U10.9) Multisystem inflammatory syndrome associated with COVID-19, unspecified: 
 • Time-linked to COVID-19: 
 -cytokine storm 
 -Kawasaki syndrome 
 -Multisystem Inflammatory Syndrome in Children (MIS-C) 
 -Pediatric Inflammatory Multisystem Syndrome (PIMS) 
 
 U11: Need for immunization against COVID-19 
 (U11.9) Need for immunization against COVID-19, unspecified: 
 This code should not be used for international comparison of rates or for coding primary mortality. This optional code is intended to be used when a person, who may or may not be sick, contacts health services for the specific purpose of receiving the COVID-19 vaccine. 
 • Preventive vaccination against COVID-19 
 
 U12: Side Effects of Therapeutic Use of COVID-19 Vaccine 
 (U12.9) Unspecified side effects of COVID-19 vaccine therapy: 
 This code is to be used as an external cause code (ie, as a subcategory under (Y59) Other and unspecified vaccines and biologicals). In addition, code from another chapter of the classification should be used to indicate the nature of the adverse effect. 
 • Correct administration of COVID-19 vaccine in preventive therapeutic use as the cause of any adverse effect.
